</div>
<p>The <b>bluethroat</b> (<i>Luscinia svecica</i>) is a small <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passerine" title="Passerine">passerine</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> that was formerly classed as a member of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thrush_(bird)" title="Thrush (bird)">thrush</a> family Turdidae, but is now more generally considered to be an <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_World_flycatcher" title="Old World flycatcher">Old World flycatcher</a>, Muscicapidae. It, and similar small <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">European</a> species, are often called <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chat_(bird)" title="Chat (bird)">chats</a>.</p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bluethroat_(Luscinia_svecica)-_Female_at_Bharatpur_I_IMG_5484.jpg" class="image"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bluethroat_(Luscinia_svecica)-_Female_at_Bharatpur_I_IMG_5484.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Female at <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keoladeo_National_Park" title="Keoladeo National Park">Keoladeo National Park</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bharatpur,_India" title="Bharatpur, India" class="mw-redirect">Bharatpur</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rajasthan" title="Rajasthan">Rajasthan</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India" title="India">India</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bluethroatred.JPG" class="image"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bluethroatred.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Red-spotted race</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>It is a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird_migration" title="Bird migration">migratory</a> insectivorous species breeding in wet <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birch" title="Birch">birch</a> wood or bushy swamp in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asia" title="Asia">Asia</a> with a foothold in western <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alaska" title="Alaska">Alaska</a>. It nests in tussocks or low in dense bushes. It winters in north <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Africa" title="Africa">Africa</a> and the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_subcontinent" title="Indian subcontinent">Indian subcontinent</a>.</p>
<p>The bluethroat is similar in size to the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_robin" title="European robin">European robin</a> at 13–14&#160;cm. It is plain brown above except for the distinctive black tail with red side patches. It has a strong white supercilium. The male has an iridescent blue bib edged below with successive black, white and rust coloured borders. Some races, such as <i>L. svecica svecica</i> (<b>red-spotted bluethroat</b>) of northern Eurasia, have a red spot in the centre of the blue bib.</p>
<p>Others, such as <i>L. svecica cyanecula</i> (<b>white-spotted bluethroat</b>) of southern and central Europe, have a white spot in the centre of the blue bib. <i>L. svecica magna</i> in Turkey has no central spot.</p>
<p>Females of all races usually have just a blackish crescent on an otherwise cream throat and breast. Newly fledged juveniles are freckled and spotted dark brown above.</p>
<p>Despite the distinctive appearance of the males, recent genetic studies show only limited variation between the forms, and confirm that this is a single species.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="Luscinia_svecica#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The male has a varied and very <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://audioblog.sonatura.com/?p=1057">imitative song</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="Luscinia_svecica#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> Its call is a typical chat <i>chack</i> noise.</p>
